Predicting Whether or Not a Book Would Be Made into a Movie: A Tutorial

By Raksha Bellary

Introduction

We've all seen some of our favorite books on the big screen. In fact, some of the most successful movies are based off of books. We're all familiar with movies like The Hunger Games, Harry Potter, The Lord of the Rings. More recently, movies like Little Women and Dune are being adapted for film. But out of so many books to choose from, what indicates whether or not a book will be chosen for a film adaptation?

We will take a look at different qualities of both books that have been made into movies and books that haven't to see if we can find a way to predict whether a book would be made into a movie or not.

First, let's import the following libraries so that we have the tools we need to get started.

Data Scraping

Now, we need data, specifically data regarding "all books" (or, more realisitcally, just a lot of books) and data regarding books that were made into movies. The first CSV file below contains data from Goodreads Best Books Ever dataset (more information about it here: https://github.com/scostap/goodreads_bbe_dataset). The URLS after it redirect you to pages with lists of books that were made into movies (they are separated into different alphabetical categories).

In [2]:

data_list = []
table = soup.find('table')
table_rows = soup.find_all('tr')

for row in table_rows:
    row_data_pts = row.find_all('td')
    row_info = [row.text.strip() for row in row_data_pts]
    if row_data_pts:

We're going to clean up the titles of the books a bit since they seem to contain publishing year and author information. For the most part, books will be easy to identify with their titles, so we will just work with that. We're also going to make the titles all lowercase in the dataframes so that they are easy to compare with our dataframe of all books later on.

In [7]:
title_end_index = -1
for index, row in df_movies_ac.iterrows():
    if '(1' in df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book']:
        title_end_index = df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book'].index('(1')
    elif '(2' in df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book']:
        title_end_index = df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book'].index('(2')
    elif '(c.' in df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book']:
        title_end_index = df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book'].index('(c.')
    else:
        title_end_index = df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book'].index('(')
    df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book'] = (df_movies_ac.at[index, 'book'][0:title_end_index-1]).lower()

The next step is to identify which books were made into movies in the dataframe containing Goodreads books data (goodreads_books_df). We will create a new column in this dataframe called "has_movie," which specifies whether a book was made into a movie (1.0) or not (0.0). As mentioned before, the title is a great identifier of a specific book for the most part, so we will iterate through the Goodreads books dataframe and cross-reference each title with the books listed in our movies dataframe. There isn't a perfect way to do this since tbe title of the same book can be written slightly differently in different datasets, so decided to go with a way that seems to be accurate for the most part (thankfully, our dataset is so large that a few mistakes won't have a huge impact): I put all the names of books that were made into movies into a single string (in lowercase, of course) and checked to see if each title in the Goodreads dataset showed up in this string.

In [12]:
unique_movies = movies_df['book'].unique()
unique_movies_string = ''.join(unique_movies)
for index, row in goodreads_books_df.iterrows():
    if goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'title'].lower() in unique_movies_string:
        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'has_movie'] = 1
    else:
        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'has_movie'] = 0

Next, we will look at average star ratings. The dataframe provides data about the number of people who rated a specific book from one to 5 stars. For each book, we will calculate the average of these ratings and place it to a new column for average star ratings.

In [31]:
avg_star_ratings = []

for index, row in goodreads_books_df.iterrows():
    ratings = []
    if str(goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'ratingsByStars']) != '[]':
        ratings_str = goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'ratingsByStars']
        ratings_str = ratings_str[1:-1].split(', ')
        for str_val in ratings_str:
            ratings.append(int(str_val[1:-1]))
        one_star_count = int(ratings[0])
        two_stars_count = int(ratings[1])
        three_stars_count = int(ratings[2])
        four_stars_count = int(ratings[3])
        five_stars_count = int(ratings[4])
        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'avg_star_rating'] = (one_star_count * 1 + two_stars_count * 2 + three_stars_count * 3 + four_stars_count * 4 + five_stars_count * 5) / goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'numRatings']
        
        if goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'has_movie'] == 1.0:
            avg_star_ratings.append({'has_movie': 1.0, 'avg_star_rating': goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'avg_star_rating']})
        else:
            avg_star_ratings.append({'has_movie': 0.0, 'avg_star_rating': goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'avg_star_rating']})
    
avg_star_ratings = pd.DataFrame(avg_star_ratings)
sns.violinplot(x = 'has_movie', y = 'avg_star_rating', data=avg_star_ratings, order=[1.0, 0.0])
plt.title('Average rating out of five stars vs. has movie or not')
plt.xlabel('has movie')
plt.xticks(range(2), ['yes', 'no'])
plt.ylabel('average star rating')
plt.show()

According to this violin plot, there does not seem to be a significant difference between average star ratings for books with movies and books without. In fact, it looks like the highest average rating occurs in a book that has not been made into a movie (probably due to a low number of readers). For both types of books, the average is somewhere around 2.0 stars.

Since it seems like the number of people who interact with a book is a sign of its popularity and might help indicate whether or not has been made into a movie or not, let's now take a look at the number of ratings for each book itself.

Now, we are going to be taking a look at the genres for each book. Most books have more than one genre listed, so we are going to find the top genres and then graph the number of books of each type (movie and no movie) for each top genre.

In [37]:
has_movie_unique_genres = {}
no_movie_unique_genres = {}

for index, row in goodreads_books_df.iterrows():
    genres = []
    if str(goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'genres']) == '[]':
        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'genres'] = []
    else:
        genres_str = goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'genres']
        genres_str = genres_str[1:-1].split(', ')
        for str_val in genres_str:
            genres.append(str_val[1:-1])
        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'genres'] = genres
        
        if goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'has_movie'] == 1.0:
            for genre in goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'genres']:
                if genre in has_movie_unique_genres:
                    has_movie_unique_genres[genre] += 1
                else:
                    has_movie_unique_genres[genre] = 1
        else:
            for genre in goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'genres']:
                if genre in no_movie_unique_genres:
                    no_movie_unique_genres[genre] += 1
                else:
                    no_movie_unique_genres[genre] = 1
                    
print('Number of unique genres of books with movies:', len(has_movie_unique_genres)) 
print('Number of unique genres of books without movies:', len(no_movie_unique_genres))

Number of unique genres of books with movies: 494
Number of unique genres of books without movies: 979

Interestingly, there are 494 unique genres for books with movies and 979 (almost double!) the amount for books without movies.

In [38]:
top_genres_has_movie = {}
top_genres_no_movie = {}
for genre in has_movie_unique_genres:
    if has_movie_unique_genres[genre] >= 500:
        top_genres_has_movie[genre] = has_movie_unique_genres[genre]
        top_genres_no_movie[genre] = no_movie_unique_genres[genre]

top_genres = top_genres_has_movie.keys()
has_movie_genre_counts = top_genres_has_movie.values()
no_movie_genre_counts = top_genres_no_movie.values()

ind = np.arange(len(top_genres_has_movie)) 
width = 0.35

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
rects1 = ax.bar(ind, has_movie_genre_counts, width, color='royalblue') 
rects2 = ax.bar(ind+width, no_movie_genre_counts, width, color='seagreen')
ax.set_ylabel('books')
ax.set_title('Scores by group and gender')
ax.set_xticks(ind + width / 2)
ax.set_xticklabels(top_genres)

ax.legend( (rects1[0], rects2[0]), ('has movie', 'no movie') )
plt.show()

The plot above graphs the number of books of each type for the top genres, which we are defining as genres found in at least 500 books that have been made into movies. Since there are more books that haven't been made into movies than those that have, it makes sense that there are more occurrances of each genre for books that have not been made into movies. So, we will recreate this graph but with ratios of the specific genre to the total number of books of a certain type (movie or no movie) to get a better sense.

In [39]:
top_genres_has_movie = {}
top_genres_no_movie = {}
for genre in has_movie_unique_genres:
    if has_movie_unique_genres[genre] >= 500:
        top_genres_has_movie[genre] = has_movie_unique_genres[genre] / sum(has_movie_unique_genres.values())
        top_genres_no_movie[genre] = no_movie_unique_genres[genre] / sum(no_movie_unique_genres.values())

top_genres = top_genres_has_movie.keys()
has_movie_genre_counts = top_genres_has_movie.values()
no_movie_genre_counts = top_genres_no_movie.values()

ind = np.arange(len(top_genres_has_movie)) 
width = 0.35

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
rects1 = ax.bar(ind, has_movie_genre_counts, width, color='royalblue') 
rects2 = ax.bar(ind+width, no_movie_genre_counts, width, color='seagreen')
ax.set_ylabel('books')
ax.set_title('Top Genres')
ax.set_xticks(ind + width / 2)
ax.set_xticklabels(top_genres)

ax.legend( (rects1[0], rects2[0]), ('has movie', 'no movie') )
plt.show()

As we can see, all of the genres occur at higher percentages in books that have movies than books that don't have movies, especially Fiction. However, this might not be a great classification tool since so many books that have not been made into movies are also in these categories.

Since the classification of whether a book has a movie or not is currently a float value, we will make a new column that has strings so that our machine learning algorithm knows does not unintentionally treat it as a continuous variable, since the output of our decision tree needs to be a category, or class (has movie or does not have movie). Our new column will have "yes" for books with movies and "no" for books without movies.

In [44]:
for index, row in goodreads_books_df.iterrows():

        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'movie'] = 'yes'
    else:
        goodreads_books_df.at[index, 'movie'] = 'no'

dep = goodreads_books_df['movie'].tolist()

96% accurate!

This seems great! Although, it seems like what really happened is our classifying decision tree played it safe by guessing "no" for our books. And to be fair, this makes sense the percentage of books that are made into movies is pretty low.

Additionally, there are so many factors that most likely play into whether or not a book is made into a movie that our data does not even begin to represent. First, Goodreads is a great place for books data, but it is not the only place that people rate or engage with books. To provide an example, Amazon Books is a pretty popular platform. Second, having connections with screenwriters or directors (or just the movie-making industry in general) could help have a book made into a movie; this may not necessarily mean being friends with them from the get-go, but it could be that already having a previous book made into a movie helps (although I would not know for sure). Finally, the content of the book itself is a very important factor that our analysis did not consider. This goes beyond genre. Within any genre, the story itself needs to be one that people want to hear, ore more accurately, see on a big screen.
